      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Welcome Back, James \uD83D\uDC4B\n\nIt's great to meet you. Five years of running experience tells me you know what it feels like to be fit — which makes being sidelined that much harder. The fact that you've got physiotherapist clearance and you're ready to build again? That's a genuinely solid foundation to work from.\n\nBefore I dive into your plan, I want to name something: returning from plantar fasciitis isn't just about being patient with the foot — it's about rebuilding confidence in your body. We're going to do this in a way that earns that trust back, step by step.\n\n---\n\n## A Few Things I Want You to Know Before We Start\n\n**Your paces, straight from your race history (Daniels' Formula):**\nYour pre-injury 10K of 44:00 gives us an easy pace of **5:25–6:12/km**. For this entire plan, *every run sits at the comfortable end of that range — or slower if your foot is talking to you.* No threshold, no intervals, no tempo. Your physio has been clear, and so am I: easy only until you're fully cleared.\n\n**Your constraint is actually your superpower right now.** Twenty minutes, three days a week, easy effort — that's not a limitation, it's a prescription for healing *without* losing your aerobic base. We're going to use it well.\n\n**Walking breaks are built in as a feature, not a fallback.** If your foot speaks up at any point, you walk. No negotiation, no ego. Walking at a brisk pace still drives cardiovascular adaptation. It's running, just slower.\n\n---\n\n## Your Return-to-Running Plan\n\n### Structure Overview\n\n| Phase | Duration | Focus | Weekly Volume |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Phase 1** | Weeks 1–3 | Reestablish habit & tissue tolerance | ~6–8 km |\n| **Phase 2** | Weeks 4–6 | Build continuity & duration | ~9–12 km |\n| **Phase 3** | Weeks 7–9 | Consolidate base, prep for clearance | ~12–15 km |\n| **Deload** | Week 4 & 8 | Recovery & adaptation | ~6–8 km |\n\n> ⚠️ **Volume never increases more than 10% week-over-week.** Deload weeks occur at weeks 4 and 8 — this isn't optional, it's when your body actually absorbs the training.\n\n---\n\n### \uD83D\uDCC5 Phase 1 — Weeks 1–3: Reestablishing the Foundation\n\n**Goal:** Build tissue tolerance in the right foot. Keep volume modest and consistent. Every run ends feeling like you *could* have done more.\n\n**Schedule:** Tuesday · Thursday · Saturday (long run slot)\n\n---\n\n#### Week 1\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run/Walk | 15 min · 5:50–6:12/km · Walk 1 min if any foot discomfort |\n| Thursday | Easy Run/Walk | 15 min · 5:50–6:12/km · Walk 1 min if any foot discomfort |\n| Saturday | Easy Run/Walk | 20 min · 5:50–6:12/km · Walk breaks as needed |\n| **Total** | | **~6.5 km** |\n\n#### Week 2\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 18 min · 5:40–6:05/km · Walk only if foot signals |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 18 min · 5:40–6:05/km |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:35–6:00/km |\n| **Total** | | **~7.5 km** |\n\n#### Week 3\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:35–6:00/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:35–6:00/km |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:30–5:55/km |\n| **Total** | | **~8.5 km** |\n\n> \uD83D\uDCAC **Coaching note:** You'll notice Weeks 2 and 3 are right in line with your recent training history (8.5 km, 3 runs in the week of March 9). That's intentional — we're not starting from scratch, we're building on what you've already done.\n\n---\n\n### \uD83D\uDCC5 Phase 2 — Weeks 4–6: Building Continuity\n\n**Goal:** Extend time on feet toward the full 20-minute cap on all runs. Solidify the 3-day habit. Start noticing that easy running feels *routine*, not effortful.\n\n**Deload at Week 4** — volume drops back to Phase 1 levels. This is where adaptation happens.\n\n---\n\n#### Week 4 — Deload \uD83D\uDD04\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 15 min · 5:50–6:12/km · Lower effort, high focus on foot sensation |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 15 min · 5:50–6:12/km |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:50–6:12/km |\n| **Total** | | **~6.5 km** |\n\n#### Week 5\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:30–5:55/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:30–5:55/km |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:25–5:50/km |\n| **Total** | | **~9.5 km** |\n\n#### Week 6\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:28–5:52/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:28–5:52/km |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:25–5:48/km |\n| **Total** | | **~10 km** |\n\n> \uD83D\uDCAC **Coaching note:** By Week 6 you'll be at or near your current weekly distance (10 km) — but arriving there from a foundation of easy, controlled effort rather than compensated movement. That distinction matters enormously for the plantar fascia.\n\n---\n\n### \uD83D\uDCC5 Phase 3 — Weeks 7–9: Consolidation & Clearance Prep\n\n**Goal:** Sustain 3 full 20-minute easy runs per week with consistency. Use this phase to gather evidence for your physio that your foot is handling load well. The conversation about progressing beyond 20 minutes — and reintroducing structured training — starts here.\n\n---\n\n#### Week 7\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:25–5:50/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:25–5:50/km |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:25–5:45/km |\n| **Total** | | **~10.5 km** |\n\n#### Week 8 — Deload \uD83D\uDD04\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 15 min · 5:50–6:12/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 15 min · 5:50–6:12/km |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:45–6:05/km |\n| **Total** | | **~6.5 km** |\n\n#### Week 9\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:25–5:45/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:25–5:45/km |\n| Saturday | Easy Run | 20 min · 5:25–5:40/km |\n| **Total** | | **~11 km** |\n\n> \uD83D\uDCAC **Coaching note:** Week 9 is a natural checkpoint. If your foot has been consistently comfortable through Phase 3, this is the moment to go back to your physio and ask about progression. At that point, we'd look at extending your Saturday long run first — then eventually reintroducing volume on weekdays before any conversation about pace work.\n\n---\n\n## How to Use This Plan Day-to-Day\n\n### The Foot Pain Decision Tree\nEvery run, before you lace up and as you run, ask yourself one question: *\"Is there foot pain?\"*\n\n- **No pain → run as planned**\n- **Mild discomfort (1–3/10) → walk 1 minute, reassess, continue easy if it settles**\n- **Moderate pain (4+/10) → stop the run, rest that day, reassess tomorrow**\n- **Pain persisting the next day → contact your physio before running again**\n\nThis isn't being overly cautious — it's how you avoid a 3-week setback becoming a 3-month one.\n\n### Effort Feel During Easy Runs\nAt 5:25–6:12/km, you should be able to hold a full conversation without gasping. If you can't, slow down. If the pace feels embarrassingly slow — that's often exactly right for early return-to-run. Your aerobic system doesn't forget as quickly as it might feel like it has.\n\n### What to Do on Off Days\nLight movement is your friend — walking, gentle stretching, calf raises (if your physio has cleared these), and foot rolling can all support recovery. This isn't \"extra training,\" it's maintenance.\n\n---\n\n## The Bigger Picture\n\nYour pre-injury 10K was 44:00. That fitness isn't gone — it's waiting. The runners who come back strongest from injuries like this are almost always the ones who took the return phase seriously rather than rushing it. You've already shown good instincts by working with your physio and knowing your limits.\n\n**What I'd love to know from you:** How is your foot feeling right now, day-to-day? And as you look at Week 1 — does the volume and structure feel manageable, or does anything jump out as a concern?"
        }
